		Ref Prompt: "USB Configuration", Help: "This field configures integrated USB controller.

Enable USB Boot Support:
When enabled, the BIOS will allow booting to USB mass storage devices (i.e. HDD, Memory Sticks, Floppy Drive, etc.).
When disabled, the BIOS will prevent booting to USB mass storage devices. This setting affects pre-boot functionality only. This setting does not affect access to the USB devices from within the operating system.

Enable External USB Ports:
When enabled, USB devices attached to the platform's USB ports are visible and available for use from within the operating system.
When disabled, any connected USB devices are not visible from within the operating system. This setting also disables USB on the Type-C port.

Note: a USB Keyboard and/or mouse connected to the platform's USB ports will continue to function within BIOS Setup if this option is disabled.

", QuestionFlags: 0x0, QuestionId: 0x20, VarStoreId: 0x0, VarStoreInfo: 0xFFFF, FormId: 0x890B
		Ref Prompt: "Dell Type-C Dock Configuration", Help: "Always Allow Dell Docks:

When set to enabled, allows connection to the Dell WD and TB family of docks (Type-C docks) independent of USB and Thunderbolt™ Adapter configuration settings.

When set to disabled, the docks will be controlled via the USB and Thunderbolt™ Adapter configuration settings.

This setting only affects the Type-C ports connected to a Dell WD or TB dock.

Setting this to enabled will override the "Enable External/Front/Rear USB Ports" and "Enable Thunderbolt™ Adapter" settings for Dell WD or TB dock connected to the system's Type-C port. The override settings are also applied to the dock's USB and Thunderbolt™ Technology ports.

", QuestionFlags: 0x0, QuestionId: 0x21, VarStoreId: 0x0, VarStoreInfo: 0xFFFF, FormId: 0x891E
		Ref Prompt: "Thunderbolt™ Adapter Configuration", Help: "Security Levels:
The settings below configure the Thunderbolt™ adapter security settings within the operating system. Security Levels are not applicable or enforced in the Pre-boot environment.
   -- No Security:                Automatically connect to devices plugged into the Thunderbolt™ port.
   -- User Authorization:   Approval is required for any new devices connected to the Thunderbolt™ port.
   -- Secure Connect:        The Thunderbolt™ adapter port will only allow connection to devices that have been configured with a shared key.
   -- Display Port Only:      Automatically connect to Display Port devices only. No Thunderbolt™ adapter or PCIe devices are allowed to connect.

Enable Thunderbolt™ Technology Support:
When enabled, the Thunderbolt™ Technology feature, and associated ports and adapters are enabled.
When disabled, the Thunderbolt™ Technology feature is disabled, and any connected Thunderbolt™ adapter devices are not available in pre-boot or within the operating system.

Enable Thunderbolt™ Adapter Boot Support:
When enabled, the following Thunderbolt™ adapter features are enabled during Pre-boot: Thunderbolt™ adapter boot support, USB device on Thunderbolt™ adapter support (including USB boot support). This allows Thunderbolt™ adapter peripheral devices and USB devices connected to the Thunderbolt™ adapter to be used during BIOS pre-boot. However, setting this to "Enabled" will override the Security Levels utilized within the operating system. When this setting is enabled, any Thunderbolt™ adapter peripherals and USB devices connected to the Thunderbolt™ adapter port prior to booting the system can be used in pre-boot. As long as the device remains connected, it will continue to function within the operating system, regardless of the Security Level set in BIOS.

Enable Thunderbolt™ Adapter Pre-boot Modules:
When enabled, this setting will allow PCIe devices that are connected through a Thunderbolt™ adapter (i.e. PCIe devices behind the Thunderbolt™ adapter) to execute the PCIe device's UEFI Option ROM(s) (if present) during pre-boot.
When disabled, this setting will prevent PCIe device Option ROMs from executing during pre-boot for PCIe devices connected behind the Thunderbolt™ adapter.

NOTE: Enabling the "Enable Thunderbolt™ Adapter Boot Support" or "Enable Thunderbolt™ Adapter Pre-boot Modules" options may allow devices connected to the Thunderbolt™ adapter during pre-boot to function in the operating system regardless of the Security Level selected in BIOS Setup.  The device will continue to operate in the operating system until it is disconnected. When reconnected while within the operating system, the device will connect according to the Security Level and previous OS authorizations.

BIOS and the TPM will use the SHA-256 hash algorithm to extend measurements into the TPM PCRs during
